---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/ui/TableOfContents';
import MethodologyCard from '../../components/ui/MethodologyCard.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I calculate the correct power supply size?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Add up the TDP/TBP of all components (primarily CPU and GPU), then apply a safety headroom factor (20% for ATX 3.1, or 35% for ATX 2.x) to absorb transient power spikes. For high-end gaming rigs, an 850W or 1000W power supply is standard."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is a larger PSU wattage bad for system efficiency?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Modern power supplies are highly efficient across a wide load range. Most PSUs hit their peak efficiency between 40% and 60% load. Having a larger capacity means your unit operates cooler, quieter, and closer to its efficiency sweet spot."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="PC PSU Sizing Guide: Wattage Headroom & Myths — PSUCheck"
  description="How to size your power supply correctly. Learn about sustained draw vs transient spikes, safety buffers, and debunking wattage calculator myths."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <a href="/methodology" class="badge badge-safe" style="text-decoration:none;">✓ Sizing Methodology Verified</a>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
          <span style="margin: 0 0.5rem; opacity: 0.5;">•</span>
          <span>1 min read</span>
        </div>
        <h1>PC PSU Sizing Guide: Wattage Headroom &amp; Myths</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          Why do wattage calculators recommend wildly different power supply sizes?
          This guide cuts through the marketing and outlines the real physics of PSU sizing.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>Sustained Draw vs. Transient Spikes</h2>
          <p>
            When a GPU manufacturer lists a <strong>TBP (Total Board Power)</strong> or TDP of 250W,
            that represents the *average* power consumed over several minutes. It does not represent
            the maximum current the card demands.
          </p>
          <p>
            Modern graphics cards experience microsecond transient excursions that draw up to
            <strong>1.5× to 1.7×</strong> of their rated power. Sizing your PSU based solely on
            an average TDP sum will result in a system that trips OCP/OPP protections and shuts
            down under load.
          </p>

          <h2>Standard Sizing Calculations</h2>
          <p>
            PSUCheck uses an engineering-first formula based on Cybenetics metrics:
          </p>
          <pre class="code-block">Recommended PSU = (CPU PL2 × 1.20) + (GPU TBP × Tier Multiplier) + Other Components + Safety Headroom</pre>
          <p>
            Where the Tier Multiplier represents the observed transient behavior of the GPU class.
            Halo-class cards like the RTX 5090 demand a larger multiplier (1.57×) due to aggressive
            boost clocks.
          </p>

          <h2>Debunking PSU Sizing Myths</h2>
          <h3>Myth 1: "I need a 1200W PSU for any gaming rig"</h3>
          <p>
            <strong>False.</strong> A standard gaming setup (e.g., Ryzen 7 7800X3D + RTX 4070 Ti SUPER)
            runs comfortably on a high-quality 750W or 850W power supply. You only need 1000W+ if
            you are pairing flagship components (Intel Core i9 + RTX 5090) or running custom liquid cooling loops.
          </p>

          <h3>Myth 2: "Buying an oversized PSU wastes power"</h3>
          <p>
            <strong>False.</strong> Under 80 PLUS standards, PSUs are most efficient at 50% load.
            If your PC draws 400W under gaming loads, a 850W PSU will operate closer to its efficiency
            sweet spot than a 500W unit running near its limit. Oversized units also generate less heat,
            meaning their fans spin slower and quieter.
          </p>

          <div style="margin-top:3rem;">
            <a href="/psu-calculator" class="btn btn-primary">Check your build requirements</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <TableOfContents client:load />
          <MethodologyCard />
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Calculators</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pc-builder">🖥️ PC Build Cost Calculator</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Other Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/atx-3-1-guide">ATX 3.1 Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-efficiency-guide">80+ Efficiency Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/budget-guide">PC Budget Guide</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
.guide-article { padding: 4rem 0; }
.guide-header { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.guide-meta { display:flex; gap: 1rem; align-items:center; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
.guide-lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-secondary); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
.guide-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .guide-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 8fr) minmax(0, 4fr); }
}
.guide-content h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content h3 { margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-size:1.1rem; }
.guide-content p, .guide-content li { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.code-block { background: var(--bg-tertiary); padding: 1rem; border-radius: var(--radius-sm); border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle); overflow-x:auto; font-family:var(--font-mono); font-size:0.75rem; margin-bottom:1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
</style>
